COWPOX, BOVINE, HUMAN - BRAZIL (SAO PAULO)
******************************************
A ProMED-mail post
<http://www.promedmail.org>
ProMED-mail is a program of the
International Society for Infectious Diseases
<http://www.isid.org>

Date: Thu 9 Jan 2003
From: ProMED-mail <promed@promedmail.org>
Source: Estado de Sao Paulo (Brazil) website, Wed 8 Jan 2003 [in
Portuguese] [edited]
<http://www.estado.estadao.com.br/suplementos/agri/2003/01/08/agri031.html>
[Translated & summarized by Mod.JW]

Cowpox has infected 37 people in Lagoinha, Sao Paulo state and
approximately 1500 head of cattle, with large pustules on the udders and on
the hands of the milkers [see photo at URL].
5 foci of cowpox, a non-fatal disease with no specific treatment, were
identified in this locality, which belongs to the dairy farming zone of Sao
Luiz do Paraitinga. Marly Ueda, a researcher at the Instituto Adolfo Lutz,
confirmed the presence of the virus, and a dermatologist at the Instituto
Butantan took samples from the 37 infected people, by which the antibodies
to the disease were found.
Cowpox is transmitted between cattle when calves suckle infected udders,
and from them to humans by contact when milking, producing the same
pustules on the hands and sometimes the ears, leaving scars. There may also
be swollen glands and fever. Without specific treatment, just antibiotics
to prevent secondary infection and fever medicines, the disease disappears
in 2 weeks, the time it takes for antibodies to appear.
Dermatologist Joao Luiz Cardoso, of the Butantan Institute, explained that
cowpox is an old problem in Brazil. It has been studied by the Biological
Institute since the 1930s, there was an epidemic a decade ago in the region
of Aracatuba, and cases in 1998 in Taboado, Mato Grosso state, and Rio
Vermelho, Goias state.
Recommended control measures are to wipe the udders with iodized alcohol
and wear rubber gloves when milking. The milk should be discarded.
Vaccine history
---------------
Cowpox was used as the first human vaccine against smallpox by the
researcher Jenner, in England. In the 18th century, when smallpox was
killing millions of people and was a serious problem even in Brazil, he
proved that English dairymaids who had contracted cowpox never caught
smallpox. He inoculated material from pustules on the cows into animals and
then humans, and found they became immune. The system was then used in
slaves in Brazil, by rubbing the infected arm of one slave against the arms
of others. After further refinement, the vaccine was so effective that
human smallpox became the first and thus far the only human disease to be
eradicated.
[Byline: Luiz Roberto Queiroz]
