ProMED-mail
<promed@promedmail.org>
[For those who are interested in the history of Jenner's early vaccination
activities, a brief history plus 3 letters written by Jenner can be found
at: <http://www.fordham.edu/halsall/mod/1798jenner-vacc.html>
ProMED-mail reported on cowpox outbreaks in the Ukraine in 2001 and in Rio
de Janeiro (state) Brazil in 1998. On a side note, one wonders whether the
cessation of smallpox vaccination worldwide is or has been leading to an
increase in human cases of cowpox. - Mod.MPP]
[The identity of the virus in this report is unclear. Possibilities are
_Vaccinia virus_ or _Pseudocowpox virus_, both of which are widespread and
associated with disease in domestic animals and their handlers. Recently
Damaso et al. (Virology 277:439-49, 2000) described the biological
properties of poxvirus isolates from skin lesions on dairy cows and milkers
during recent exanthem episodes in Cantagalo County, Rio de Janeiro State,
Brazil. These isolates proved to be more similar to Vaccinia virus than
Cowpox virus. They named the virus Cantagalo virus and concluded that their
isolates represented a single strain derived from the Vaccinia virus used
as vaccine in Brazil.
The virus in question is unlikely to be _Cowpox virus_. The reservoir hosts
of Cowpox virus, despite its name, are a wide range of rodents. For
example, in the UK the reservoir hosts of cowpox virus are predominantly
bank voles, field voles, and wood mice. Cowpox virus has been found only in
Europe and adjacent regions of Russia. Cowpox virus occasionally spreads to
other animals, including domestic cats, cattle, humans, and a variety of
zoo animals (predominantly felids). Currently infection with cowpox virus
is more commonly seen in domestic cats, from which it is occasionally
transmitted to humans. Indeed cowpox virus infection in cats can be a more
severe disease than in humans or cattle.
Poxviruses are subject to progressive evolution by mutation and
recombination. The cowpox virus of Jenner's time and the virus currently
designated cowpox virus cannot be identical. Indeed, cowpox lesion material
was gradually replaced over the years by other smallpox vaccine
preparations. The origin of the current smallpox vaccine, _Vaccinia virus_,
is obscure, and it may have evolved by recombination between Variola
(smallpox) virus, viruses from cowpox lesions, and rodent viruses such as
cowpox virus. Phylogenetic analyses suggest that _Camelpox virus_ rather
than Cowpox virus is the closest extant relative of Variola virus. - Mod.CP]
